# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: monetdb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:monetdb/blog] Over the years we have published a number of blog posts to highlight new features or explained innovations.
[src:monetdb/blog] Below you find the timeline and access to those original documents.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:monetdb/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:monetdb/documentation-user-guide] With its origins in the database research community, MonetDB continues to break new ground as a database management system applicable to real-world use cases.
[src:monetdb/documentation-user-guide] Its compatibility with a wide range of platforms renders it easy to set up, use and administer.
[src:monetdb/documentation-user-guide] MonetDB comprises an elaborate ecosystem capable of addressing complex data management challenges.
[src:monetdb/documentation-user-guide] The topics listed below allow new users to gain a foothold in the MonetDB suite.
[src:monetdb/documentation-user-guide] Particular attention has been placed on the SQL syntax and features in order to bolster the process of getting an application up and running.
[src:monetdb/documentation] This guide aims at people primarily interested into using MonetDB directly to develop SQL-based applications using its command-line-interface or developing JDBC & ODBC applications.
[src:monetdb/documentation] This section provides an in-depth documentation for server administrators.
[src:monetdb/documentation] There is information about installation (from source), updates, security and roles, backup and monitoring.
[src:monetdb/documentation] This guide aims at database application developers as well as those that seek to improve the MonetDB code base itself.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:monetdb/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Data mining projects in the 1990s required improved analytical database support.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] This resulted in a CWI spin-off called Data Distilleries, which used early MonetDB implementations in its analytical suite.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Data Distilleries eventually became a subsidiary of SPSS in 2003, which in turn was acquired by IBM in 2009.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB in its current form was first created in 2002 by doctoral student Peter Boncz and professor Martin L.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Kersten as part of the 1990s' MAGNUM research project at University of Amsterdam.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] It was initially called simply Monet, after the French impressionist painter Claude Monet.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The first version under an open-source software license (a modified version of the Mozilla Public License) was released on September 30, 2004.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] When MonetDB version 4 was released into the open-source domain, many extensions to the code base were added by the MonetDB/CWI team, including a new SQL front end, supporting the SQL:2003 standard.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB introduced innovations in all layers of the DBMS: a storage model based on vertical fragmentation, a modern CPU-tuned query execution architecture that often gave MonetDB a speed advantage over the same algorithm over a typical interpreter-based RDBMS.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] It was one of the first database systems to tune query optimization for CPU caches.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB includes automatic and self-tuning indexes, run-time query optimization, and a modular software architecture.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] By 2008, a follow-on project called X100 (MonetDB/X100) started, which evolved into the VectorWise technology.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] VectorWise was acquired by Actian Corporation, integrated with the Ingres database and sold as a commercial product.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] In 2011 a major effort to renovate the MonetDB codebase was started.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] As part of it, the code for the MonetDB 4 kernel and its XQuery components were frozen.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] In MonetDB 5, parts of the SQL layer were pushed into the kernel.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The resulting changes created a difference in internal APIs, as it transitioned from MonetDB Instruction Language (MIL) to MonetDB Assembly Language (MAL).
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Older, no-longer maintained top-level query interfaces were also removed.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] First was XQuery, which relied on MonetDB 4 and was never ported to version 5.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The experimental Jaql interface support was removed with the October 2014 release.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] With the July 2015 release, MonetDB gained support for read-only data sharding and persistent indices.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] In this release the deprecated streaming data module DataCell was also removed from the main codebase in an effort to streamline the code.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] In addition, the license has been changed into the Mozilla Public License, version 2.0.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB architecture is represented in three layers, each with its own set of optimizers.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The front end is the top layer, providing query interface for SQL, with SciQL and SPARQL interfaces under development.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Queries are parsed into domain-specific representations, like relational algebra for SQL, and optimized.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The generated logical execution plans are then translated into MonetDB Assembly Language (MAL) instructions, which are passed to the next layer.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The middle or back-end layer provides a number of cost-based optimizers for the MAL.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The bottom layer is the database kernel, which provides access to the data stored in Binary Association Tables (BATs).
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Each BAT is a table consisting of an Object-identifier and value columns, representing a single column in the database.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB internal data representation also relies on the memory addressing ranges of contemporary CPUs using demand paging of memory mapped files, and thus departing from traditional DBMS designs involving complex management of large data stores in limited memory.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Query recycling is an architecture for reusing the byproducts of the operator-at-a-time paradigm in a column store DBMS.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Recycling makes use of the generic idea of storing and reusing the results of expensive computations.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Unlike low-level instruction caches, query recycling uses an optimizer to pre-select instructions to cache.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The technique is designed to improve query response times and throughput, while working in a self-organizing fashion.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The authors from the CWI Database Architectures group, composed of Milena Ivanova, Martin Kersten, Niels Nes and Romulo Goncalves, won the "Best Paper Runner Up" at the ACM SIGMOD 2009 conference for their work on Query Recycling.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB was one of the first databases to introduce Database Cracking.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Database Cracking is an incremental partial indexing and/or sorting of the data.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] It directly exploits the columnar nature of MonetDB.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Cracking is a technique that shifts the cost of index maintenance from updates to query processing.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The query pipeline optimizers are used to massage the query plans to crack and to propagate this information.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The technique allows for improved access times and self-organized behavior.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Database Cracking received the ACM SIGMOD 2011 J.Gray best dissertation award.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] A number of extensions exist for MonetDB that extend the functionality of the database engine.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Due to the three-layer architecture, top-level query interfaces can benefit from optimizations done in the backend and kernel layers.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB/SQL is a top-level extension, which provides complete support for transactions in compliance with the SQL:2003 standard.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB/GIS is an extension to MonetDB/SQL with support for the Simple Features Access standard of Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC).
[src:monetdb/monetdb] SciQL an SQL-based query language for science applications with arrays as first class citizens.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] SciQL allows MonetDB to effectively function as an array database.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] SciQL is used in the European Union PlanetData Archived 2014-05-30 at the Wayback Machine and TELEIOS project, together with the Data Vault technology, providing transparent access to large scientific data repositories.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Data Vaults map the data from the distributed repositories to SciQL arrays, allowing for improved handling of spatio-temporal data in MonetDB.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] SciQL will be further extended for the Human Brain Project.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Data Vault is a database-attached external file repository for MonetDB, similar to the SQL/MED standard.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The Data Vault technology allows for transparent integration with distributed/remote file repositories.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] It is designed for scientific data data exploration and mining, specifically for remote sensing data.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] There is support for the GeoTIFF (Earth observation), FITS (astronomy), MiniSEED (seismology) and NetCDF formats.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The data is stored in the file repository in the original format, and loaded in the database in a lazy fashion, only when needed.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The system can also process the data upon ingestion, if the data format requires it.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] As a result, even very large file repositories can be efficiently analyzed, as only the required data is processed in the database.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The data can be accessed through either the MonetDB SQL or SciQL interfaces.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The Data Vault technology was used in the European Union's TELEIOS project, which was aimed at building a virtual observatory for Earth observation data.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB has a SAM/BAM module for efficient processing of sequence alignment data.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Aimed at the bioinformatics research, the module has a SAM/BAM data loader and a set of SQL UDFs for working with DNA data.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The module uses the popular SAMtools library.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] MonetDB/RDF is a SPARQL-based extension for working with linked data, which adds support for RDF and allowing MonetDB to function as a triplestore.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Under development for the Linked Open Data 2 project.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Similarly to the embedded R UDFs in MonetDB, the database now has support for UDFs written in Python/NumPy.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The implementation uses Numpy arrays (themselves Python wrappers for C arrays), as a result there is limited overhead - providing a functional Python integration with speed matching native SQL functions.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The Embedded Python functions also support mapped operations, allowing user to execute Python functions in parallel within SQL queries.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The practical side of the feature gives users access to Python/NumPy/SciPy libraries, which can provide a large selection of statistical/analytical functions.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Following the release of an embedded driver for R and R UDFs in MonetDB (MonetDB/R), the authors created an embedded version of MonetDB in R called **MonetDBLite**, embedded versions for Python and Java followed.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] They are distributed as embeddable packages, removing the need to manage a database server, required for the previous API integrations.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The DBMS runs within the process itself, eliminating socket communication and serialisation overhead - greatly improving efficiency.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The idea behind it is to easily embed an SQLite-like package with the performance of an in-memory optimized columnar store.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] A number of former extensions have been deprecated and removed from the stable code base over time.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] Some notable examples include an XQuery extension removed in MonetDB version 5; a JAQL extension, and a streaming data extension called *Data Cell*.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The MonetDB Foundation is the independent non-profit organisation behind MonetDB.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The foundation holds the intellectual property (IP) of MonetDB and is dedicated to advance the development and long-term maintenance of MonetDB.
[src:monetdb/monetdb] The foundation is funded by charitable donations.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:monetdb/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
